  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3465379788" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3465379788" />
    <a title="Marta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2168708-marta"><img alt="Marta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1271458432p2/2168708.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3465379788?book_show_action=true">Aug 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marta" href="/user/show/2168708-marta">Marta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2168708-marta?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2168708-marta?shelf=library">library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2168708-marta?shelf=audio">audio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3465379788" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4967513779011854732"><blockquote>14th century marriage counselor:<br/><br/>Man: I am having trouble with my wife. She often talks her mind.<br/>Counselor: You do not beat her enough.<br/><br/>Man goes home. Beats his wife senseless in the presence of his approving friend. They live happily ever after. No more talking back.</blockquote><br/><br/>One hundred stories in the time of the plague, told by ten young women and man, offer an insight into contemporary life, and the thoughts and ethics of people at the time. As Boccaccio was Italian, most stories involve wealthy Italian</span>
  <span id="freeText4967513779011854732" style="display:none"><blockquote>14th century marriage counselor:<br /><br />Man: I am having trouble with my wife. She often talks her mind.<br />Counselor: You do not beat her enough.<br /><br />Man goes home. Beats his wife senseless in the presence of his approving friend. They live happily ever after. No more talking back.</blockquote><br /><br />One hundred stories in the time of the plague, told by ten young women and man, offer an insight into contemporary life, and the thoughts and ethics of people at the time. As Boccaccio was Italian, most stories involve wealthy Italian merchants, although there are some about princes and kings, and some about common folk or peasants. The stories are meant for entertainment, especially that of idle women, as Boccaccio states in the afterword. Many are bawdy, often about lover’s mischiefs, clever tricks people play on each other, women who cheat, lecherous priests, etc. Boccaccio says he did not invent the stories, but collected them - and I believe him as at least one story, the last one, also occurs in The Canterbury Tales, with different names, but same content.<br /><br />What stands out in this collection for a modern woman is how completely subjugated women were to their husbands and families. Men had the right to beat them, even kill them. The same was true for children. In the last story (the one that is also in the Canterbury Tales), a man marries a very obedient woman and proceeds to submit her to terrible emotional torture, to test her constancy. She has two children, whom he takes away and makes her believe he killed them. She takes it uncomplainingly. Then she sends her home in only a shift, saying he is divorcing her to marry a young bride. Then he requires her to arrange the wedding and greet the bride. She does this without complaint, albeit the servants grumble. Then he finally reveals this was only a test, the young bride is actually their daughter who was raised by his cousin, and they all reunite and are happy ever after. He declares he has the best wife and he loves her very much, because what could be more desirable in a woman then idly watch the killing of her children and her own humiliation with meek obedience? And what shows a man’s love more than making her believe he killed their children? Clearly, men had strange ideas of domestic bliss. <br /><br />Well, ok, this was an extreme story, and the youngsters debated it quite a bit. There were many others with clever women who played their husbands, to cheat on them; or men who would not leave them alone, to preserve their honor. But women were considered weak both in body and mind, and they naturally needed guidance by men. A long speech about this is written into the mouth of one of the young women; she also tells the story of the beaten wife, with the moral that women just <i>need</i> to be corrected, and beatings were necessary. <br /><br />In some of the other stories, love of women is traded among men, like she is not even a person whose choice should be asked. One poor very beautiful shipwrecked lady, who is unfortunate enough not yo speak the local language, is passed around among various gentlemen as a kept woman, because they “fell in love with her”, meaning, they wanted to f*ck her and could not care about whether she consented. In another story about generosity, a man gives up his bethrothed to his best friend who has fatally fallen in love with her. The story wexes about the two men’s love for the woman and each other, but the idea of asking the woman whom she loves never even comes up. Love only affects men, even if the object is a woman.<br /><br />The power of these stories is the rare insight into domestic life, as much of the material that survives from those days is religious or other high-minded literature. That’s the reason women figure strongly as well, and the reason they are still being read - we can still relate to these people, even if many of their mores are outdated (thank goodness). <br /><br />I listened to this - 30 hours is long, but as the stories are each pretty short, it does not feel drawn out. The format is pretty ideal to listen to while doing chores or walking. I think the narration helped a lot, as many sentences are longwinded. Frederick Davidson broke them up into digestible chunks with emphases and breaks. Reading would have been harder.<br /><br />In between the stories we have long discussions on what the participants were doing, which was rather boring and repetitive, but relatively easy to tune out. There are also longwinded justifications and morals of the stories - those are easily skippable while reading, or tuned out while doing something else. <br /><br />The crux are the one hundred stories, which are entertaining. Delivered during a pandemic... which is timely.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4967513779011854732" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


